article.headline: Overmatched Syracuse drops 7th straight
article.linkText: No. 1 UConn easily wins eighth in a row
article.story:
SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) -- When UConn missed its first six shots
against Syracuse, the Huskies simply shrugged it off and won again.

Handily.

Diana Taurasi and Ann Strother each scored 10 points in the
first half to give Connecticut (No. 1 ESPN/USA Today, No. 2 AP) a huge lead, and the Huskies
beat Syracuse 82-38 on Wednesday night.

It was the eighth straight win for Connecticut (19-2, 9-1 Big
East) and the seventh straight loss for Syracuse (6-15, 3-8).

The Huskies didn't take long to take charge. After missing those
shots and making only one of their first seven 3-pointers, they
quickly settled down and outscored the Orangewomen 22-2 over the
final seven minutes of the first half.

"The first three minutes we pretty much had any shot we
wanted," said Taurasi, who swished three straight 3-pointers to
key the surge. "We just couldn't knock them down, but once we hit
one they started dropping. We weren't too worried."

After consecutive baskets by Tracy Harbut moved the Orangewomen
to 21-13 with 7:12 left, the Huskies put the game away behind
Taurasi's hot hand and Strother, who hit a turnaround baseline
jumper and three layups as the Huskies raced to a 43-15 halftime
lead.

"They're not going to stay that cold. We knew that," said
Syracuse point guard Julie McBride, who paced the Orangewomen with
11 points but was only 1-for-9 on 3-pointers. "They're better
shooters than that. We played good defense the first couple of
minutes. We were ready to go. But they beat us by 44. That's a lot
of points."

Barbara Turner led UConn with 13 points, Ashley Battle had 11
and Jessica Moore had nine points and 10 rebounds. Taurasi and
Strother played sparingly in the second half and neither scored
after the break.

The Huskies have lost only one of their last 127 games against
unranked opponents, and that lone defeat is fresh on their minds.
It came in January at Notre Dame. The Irish stunned them 66-51 just
10 days after Duke had rallied from 18 points behind for a 68-67
victory on UConn's home court -- before a sellout crowd and a
national television audience.

"Everybody's just matured and really started playing (since
Notre Dame)," Moore said. "There are no more lulls. Everybody is
just filling their role, doing their part and getting the job done.
I think everyone has put more pressure on themselves. People aren't
just going to roll over for us. We need to come out and play, and
that's what we've been doing."

UConn shot 50.8 percent for the game and finished 10-for-24 on
3-pointers. The Huskies also outrebounded the Orangewomen 42-30 and
held them to 28.6 percent shooting.

"We did our best out there," said first-year Syracuse coach
Keith Cieplicki, who has only nine players after losing three to
academic problems. "Connecticut is obviously where they are
because of their personnel and the way they play. They've got a lot
of weapons. They're the benchmark for this league and the
country."
